":"okolo 1520","1549":"1549","1537":"1537","England":"Anglie"},"da":{"about 1520–":"omkring 1520–Afdød","1522–Female":"1522–Afdød","1496–1537":"1496–1537","1520–Male":"1520–Afdød","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","1496":"1496","about 1520":"omkring 1520","1549":"1549","1537":"1537","England":"England"},"nl":{"about 1520–":"circa 1520–Overleden","1522–Female":"1522–Overleden","1496–1537":"1496–1537","1520–Male":"1520–Overleden","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","1496":"1496","about 1520":"circa 1520","1549":"1549","1537":"1537","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1520–":"about 1520–Deceased","1522–Female":"1522–Deceased","1496–1537":"1496–1537","1520–Male":"1520–Deceased","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","1496":"1496","about 1520":"about 1520","1549":"1549","1537":"1537","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fenn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name in south-east England for someone who lived in a low-lying marshy area, from Middle English <i>fen(ne)</i> ‘fen, marsh’ (Old English <i>fenn</i>).","South German: topographic name from Old High German <i>fenni</i>, Middle Low German and Old Frisian <i>fenne</i> ‘bog’. Compare   Fehn  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 馮, see   Feng   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Fehn","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a bog or marsh, from <i>fehn</i> ‘bog’.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of the three farms in southeastern Norway named Fen, probably from Old Norse <i>Fávin</i>, of which the second element is <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’; the first element is unexplained."]},{"name":"Fenner","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>fen(ne)</i> ‘fen, marsh’ (Old English <i>fenn</i>) + <i>-er</i>, a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a marsh or fen. Fenn Place in Worth in Sussex had owners called <i>atte Fenne</i>, who in the time of King Henry VI (1421–1471) apparently changed their name to <i>Fenner</i>. See   Fenn  .","English: variant of <b>Fainer</b>, from Middle English <i>feiner</i>, <i>fener</i> ‘haymonger, one who sells hay’ (Old French <i>fenier</i>), or perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>feiner</i> ‘inventor; hypocrite’.","South German and Swiss German: occupational name for an ensign or standard bearer, from Middle High German <i>vener</i>, an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>vane</i> ‘flag’. See also   Fenrich  ."]},{"name":"Fenning","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>fen(ne)</i> ‘fen, marsh’ (Old English <i>fenn</i>) + <i>-ing</i>, for someone who lived by a fen or marsh. Compare   Fenn  ."]},{"name":"Finner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: topographic name from an agent derivative of Old High German <i>fenni</i>, Middle Low German and Old Frisian <i>fenne</i> ‘bog’ (see   Fenn  ).","German: ethnic name for a Finn (see   Finn   4)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":49,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"William Fenn was born about 1520, in England. He had at least 1 daughter with Alice Ransom."},"et":{"about 1520–":"umbes 1520–Surnud","1522–Female":"1522–Surnud","1496–1537":"1496–1537","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","1496":"1496","about 1520":"umbes 1520","1549":"1549","1537":"1537","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1520–":"noin 1520–Kuollut","1522–Female":"1522–Kuollut","1496–1537":"1496–1537","1520–Male":"1520–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","1496":"1496","about 1520":"noin 1520","1549":"1549","1537":"1537","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1520–":"environ 1520–Décédé","1522–Female":"1522–Décédée","1496–1537":"1496–1537","1520–Male":"1520–Décédé","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1522":"1522","1520":"1520","1496":"1496","about 1520":"environ 1520","1549":"1549","1537":"1537","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Fenn est né environ 1520, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec 